### PHP OOP - Classes and Objects

PHP supports object-oriented programming with classes and objects.

### Defining a Class

```php
<?php
class Car {
    // Properties
    public $brand;
    public $color;

    // Method
    public function start() {
        return "The $this->color $this->brand is starting";
    }
}
?>
```

### Creating Objects

```php
<?php
$myCar = new Car();
$myCar->brand = "Toyota";
$myCar->color = "Red";
echo $myCar->start(); // The Red Toyota is starting
?>
```

### Visibility Modifiers

| Modifier | Same Class | Subclasses | Outside |
|----------|-----------|------------|---------|
| `public` | Yes | Yes | Yes |
| `protected` | Yes | Yes | No |
| `private` | Yes | No | No |

### $this Keyword

`$this` refers to the current object instance.

```php
<?php
class User {
    public $name;

    public function setName($name) {
        $this->name = $name;
    }

    public function getName() {
        return $this->name;
    }
}
?>
```

### Static Methods and Properties

```php
<?php
class MathHelper {
    public static $pi = 3.14159;

    public static function square($num) {
        return $num * $num;
    }
}

echo MathHelper::$pi;       // Access static property
echo MathHelper::square(5); // 25
?>
```

> **Key Point:** Use `->` to access object properties/methods and `::` (Scope Resolution Operator) for static members.
